to be due to boundary effects caused by these structures
since deflections of the CSTs in this area are forced to be
partially internally reflected, thereby inducing a local fo-
cusing or increase in amplitude as the waves pass
through this region. Once the waves have passed through
this area, they attenuate nearly linearly as they propagate
towards the top of the CSTs. To demonstrate this behav-
ior, we show below in Fig. 7 the
y
-component of the
shear displacement along the right CST of volunteer 3.
The spatial-spectral filter was performed on the data,
and the Helmholtz decomposition was used to separate
the displacement into its shear and longitudinal compo-
nents. It should be mentioned that the amplitude of the
raw data is
80 microns, but due to the filtering proce-
dure the resulting amplitude is on the order of 1.2
microns.
This rather large difference in amplitude is
due to the removal of many wavenumber components
which are not propagating along the particular CST path-
way. In Fig. 7, we show the real and imaginary parts of
this displacement, as well as the magnitude along the
pathway. As can be observed, the shear wave amplitude
increases from the bottom of the CST to a peak value
around 1.6 cm from the base, then attenuates nearly line-
arly towards the top of the CST. This displacement is
utilized in Eq. 4b for a solution of the shear coefficient
C
, and the solution for this inversion is shown in Fig.
5. As shown in Fig. 5g, the blue dotted line corresponds
to volunteer 3, and the attenuation crosses zero at
exactly the point of amplitude inflection of Fig. 7. Addi-
tionally, the wave velocity obtained from the wavelength
in Fig. 7 is around 2.2 m/s, which is nearly exactly the
value determined using Eq. 8 and the moduli obtained
from the inversion, and is shown in Fig. 5e (blue dotted
line). This, however, is only one explanation for this
